## 🔍 1. Understanding the Problem

**"Why hasn't this been solved before? Why are banks still doing this manually?"**
> XBRL taxonomy structures are highly regulator-specific and change frequently. Generic tools don't understand RBI/MAS specific conventions. Banks ended up building one-off solutions per report because no universal engine existed.

**"How big is this problem? Is it just a Citi problem or does every bank face this?"**
> Every bank that submits XBRL regulatory reports faces this — HSBC, Standard Chartered, DBS, every bank operating in India, Singapore, Hong Kong etc. The problem is industry-wide.

**"How many reports does Citi currently submit and how many are pending?"**
> Currently 3 reports are live. Six Basel III reports and other series are pending. At 2–4 weeks per report manually, that backlog alone justifies this engine.

---

## 💡 2. Understanding the Solution

**"Why do you need AI for this? Can't you just write smarter Python/Java code?"**
> You can handle simple cases with code, but real reports have ambiguous data type mappings, multi-dimensional context combinations, missing dimension mappings, and pipe transformations that require reasoning — not just rules. Every rule you hardcode needs updating when the taxonomy changes. LLM adapts automatically.

**"What exactly does the LLM do vs what does the code do?"**
> Code does 100% of the data extraction (deterministic, reliable). LLM only handles the intelligent mapping step — deciding correct context IDs, units, pipe transformations, and handling ambiguities. Java does the final conversion unchanged.

**"What happens if the LLM generates a wrong template?"**
> We have a self-correction loop. The system validates the generated template fact-by-fact against expected output. If accuracy is below 95%, it automatically feeds the errors back to the LLM for correction — up to 3 iterations. We've already validated 100% match on R396 and 89.1% on R322.

**"Which LLM are you using? Are you locked into one vendor?"**
> The engine is LLM-agnostic by design — it works with GPT-4, Claude, Gemini, or Devin. We deliberately avoided vendor lock-in so Citi can switch to whichever model performs best or is approved for enterprise use.

