## 📈 4. Business Impact & ROI

**"What is the actual cost saving?"**
> Each report currently requires 2–4 weeks of a specialized Java developer's time. With 100+ reports across 5 countries, that's potentially 200–400 weeks of developer time saved. The engine reduces per-report effort by 87–95%.

**"You mentioned scaling to 100+ reports across 5 countries — how realistic is that?"**
> Very realistic. The engine is report-agnostic — it takes any taxonomy ZIP + Excel spec as input. India (RBI), Singapore (MAS), Hong Kong (HKMA), Australia (APRA), Thailand (BOT) all use XBRL. Same engine, different taxonomy ZIP.

**"What is the risk if this fails in production?"**
> Low, because the existing Java XMLConverter is completely unchanged. If the AI-generated template has errors, the validation layer catches it before it ever reaches the Java converter. The existing system acts as a safety net.

